    <h1>CON&#xAD;VERT CHILD&#xAD;CARE LEAVE TO PAR&#xAD;ENT-CARE LEAVE</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201127/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-27"><time>2020-11-27</time></a>
        - <span>FORUM</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Ev­ery year, many com­pa­nies give em­ploy­ees about five days of paid child­care leave per child un­der the age of 12, and three days of paid par­ent-care leave to cover both par­ents.</p>
    <p>Af­ter their chil­dren grow up, em­ploy­ees would surely need more days of par­ent-care leave to take care of their aged par­ents.</p>
    <p>Per­haps com­pa­nies can ex­plore al­low­ing em­ploy­ees who are no longer en­ti­tled to paid child­care leave to have more days of paid par­ent-care leave to at­tend to their aged par­ents’ needs.</p>
    <p>Lim Lih Mei</p>

